We know it won't be below 2%. Current inflation expectations are 2.6% over the next 10 years, and I believe those expectations are likely to rise rather than fall. Producer price inflation is 11% which means that producers have not been passing their full rising costs on to the consumer. This is a leading indicator for the CPI. No serious investor will tie up their money for 10 years at an amount below their inflation expectations. They will want inflation plus a little extra for profit and risk. Although the FED could push the 10-year rate below 2% if they start asset purchases again.

"Debt markets came under heavy selling pressure in April, with the US yield on the 10-year note, which sets the tone for corporate and household borrowing costs worldwide, surging above 2.63%, its highest level since March 2019. Investors anticipated an aggressive looming policy tightening cycle as major central banks sought to tame inflation, currently running at records levels in Europe and 40-year highs in the US. Market moves were compounded by surprisingly hawkish comments from Federal Reserve Governor Lael Brainard, which said tightening would include a swift reduction in the balance sheet and steady interest rate increases. Meantime, Germany's 10-year Bund yield, the benchmark for Europe, rose to as high as 0.65%, closing in on its highest level since May 2018." https://tradingeconomics.com/united-states/government-bond-yield

I've been overweighting the 2-3% bin, but am now asking myself why the crowd puts a 36% chance of 1-2%. I don't want to discount the crowd's opinion. There is a chance that we are entering a period of stagflation. War, materials shortages, food shortages, inflation, and possibly lower economic growth could persist until the end of the year. There is a long time left until the close of this question. The Fed controls short-term interest rates, but usually not long-term rates. In extreme circumstances, such as the past two years of COVID, the Fed bought long-term treasuries and forced interest rates below what would otherwise have been the market rate.

The overall trend since the 1980s has been lower yields. I don't see that changing by 30 Dec 2022. The global economic system seems to be predicated on low Treasury yields. 0-2% is now the "comfortable" range. We are seeing rolling waves of inflation in specific sectors but it doesn't seem to be a phenomenon so widespread that it can drive Treasury yields higher. Negative yields for Treasuries would seem to have big, disruptive implications for the global economic system so I think policymakers will resist that from happening. I don't think any transformative technology (e.g. fusion energy) will become mature in time to create new growth prospects for the global economy (i.e. you can't have 5% yields without major growth).
